The six pillars of the well-architected framework are:

    Operational excellence - how to support development and run workloads, gain insight into operations, 
        and continuously improve processes

    Security - how to use cloud technologies to protect data, systems, and assets

    Reliability - whether the workload performs its task consistently and correctly when expected to. 
        this includes the ability to operate and test the workload through its full lifecycle. 

    Performance efficiency - using compute resources efficiently to meet system requirements, 
        and maintaining that efficiency as demand changes and technologies evolve
    
    Cost optimization - making cloud systems deliver business value at the lowest price point 

    Sustainability - reducing energy consumption and increasing efficiency 
        by maximizing the benefits of provisioned resources and minimizing the total resources required. 


Some AWS terminology: 

    component - the code, configuration, and AWS Resources that together deliver a requirement. 

    workload - a set of components that together deliver business value

    architecture - how components work together in a workload

    milestones - these mark key changes in the architecture as it evolves through the product lifecycle 

    technology portfolio - the collection of workloads required for the business to operate 


General principles to facilitate good architecture in the cloud: 

    - stop guessing your capacity needs, you could guess wrong. 
        Instead, you should be scaling in and out automatically 

    - test your systems at production scale. 
        this is far less expensive now since you only pay for the test environment while it's running.

    - automate the architecture, and experiment while you do it. 
        Since you can create and replicate workloads at low cost with little effort, 
        you can monitor the impact your changes have and easily adjust or revert to previous configs if needed.

    - allow the architecture to evolve. 
        Traditionally this wasn't possible, but cloud systems can evolve their architecture much more easily. 
        You can take advantage of technological innovation much easier, for example. 
        You can adjust the architecture as scale increases or requirements change. 

    - use data to drive architectural decisions. 
        Cloud infrastructure is code, so you can use data collected from it to guide architectural decisions.

    - simulate events in production to test how your architecture and business processes deal with them.

=================================================
OPERATIONAL EXCELLENCE
=================================================

Operational excellence focuses on aligning technical execution with business objectives (which evolve). 
    By using automation and metrics, teams streamline delivery and monitor workload health to make informed decisions.
    This approach enables organizations to quickly adapt to shifting requirements, driving ongoing improvements. 

Operational Excellence design principles: 

    - Organize teams (and their workflows) around business goals. 
        Leadership must provide a clear vision - it incentivizes efficiency, agility, and measurable results. 

    - Maintain metrics and logging of performance, reliability, and cost. 
        These are actionable. They can be used to establish clear success metrics, to make informed decisions, 
        and to resolve problems early on.

    - Safely automate where possible. 
        Treat infrastructure, configurations, and procedures as code. 
        Automation ensures consistency and reduces human error. 
        You should still have safety mechanisms (like error thresholds or approval steps) to maintain some human control. 

    - Make frequent, small, reversible changes. 
        This limits the potential damage of a single failure, and makes it easier to undo the change.

    - Continuously reevaluate and update operational playbooks as the system evolves. 
        Regularly review these procedures with the team to identify gaps and get everyone on board. 

    - Simulate failure scenarios to identify problems and assess how the team responds. 
        Adjust your architecture and procedures based on the results. 

    - Learn from every operational event and metric. 
        Document the lessons learned and share them with the team. 

    - Use managed services to minimize maintenance and infrastructure management. 
        This reduces operational load on the team, allowing them to focus on their unique business requirements.


Operational excellence is a human-centric discipline. It aligns technical efforts with the business objectives. 

Establishing shared goals ensures all team members understand their role in the broader organization. 
    Leadership should determine these goals by weighing trade offs (i.e. speed to market vs costs). 
    
You should also maintain a central risk registry. 
    This is a document used to identify, track, and manage all risks that could impact operations.
    It enables leadership to plan for handling problems instead of just reacting to them. 

It's also important that every application, platform, or procedure has an identifiable owner. 
    This prevents the "bystander effect", where problems go ignored because no one feels responsibility for them. 

Similarly, it's important that there are formal agreements on how teams interact. These expectations should be documented. 

Leaders also need to promote a culture (through their attitude) that encourages best practices, risk escalation, 
    and experimentation without fear of failure.

It's also important that leaders are able to get feedback. 
    Regular reviews w/ the Well-Architected Tool is one way of getting continuous feedback. 
    Continuous feedback is important for adapting operations to changing business conditions. 

Observability (metrics, logs, traces, etc.) is also critical (it's the first step to building resilient systems). 
    By properly observing the system, problems can be identified early on and fixed before they get bigger.

Deployments should be frequent, incremental, and reversible. 
    Smaller updates reduce the blast radius of a potential failure, making it easier to debug and roll back.
    CD is enabled by CI - automated testing and fast PR feedback 

Infrastructure, policies, and procedures should be code (typically in the form of templates).
    This ensures consistency in development, test, and production.
    There should also be supporting documentation (playbooks and runbooks) to guide the team through incidents and routine tasks. 
    Often teams will conduct "pre-mortems", where they prepare for potential failures beforehand. 

Good operations teams establish baselines for their metrics, and setup alerts at thresholds. 

It's also important to gather metrics on the operations effort itself, such as deployment speeds and incident response times.
    This helps to identify problems in the operations and set goals for improvement.

Operational events that are understood should be handled using runbooks, which are written beforehand. 
    More complex investigations are guided by playbooks.

Every alert should have a dedicated owner and a defined escalation path. 
    This ensures the right people get engaged based on urgency / business impact.
    Response strategies should also be prioritized based on t heir impact on the customer. 
    To handle scenarios where standard procedures don't apply, high level decision makers should be identified in advance. 

Dashboards and notifications should be used to keep everyone in the org aligned (business leaders, developers, ops). 

Also try to script / automate the respones to recurring events, where possible. This can ensure a more consistent, rapid response.  

It's critical to conduct post-incident analysis of every customer-impacting event.
    This allows temas to identify root causes and correct them.
    The root causes should be communicated broadly to ensure the entire organization learns from the event. 

Beyond the team level, it's important to identify organization level issues too. 
    Regular retrospectives and centralized analytics (for shared trend analysis) are two ways of doing this. 
    One goal here is to ensure that lessons learned by one team benefit the organization as a whole. 

Lastly, it's important to maintain a safe environemnt for experimentation.
    This is facilitated by maintaining distinct environments (development, staging, production) 
    This encourages innovation by making failures non-threatening.

