SECURITY
=================================================

The security pillar is about protecting data, systems, and assets. 

The best practices for securing a workload cover 7 areas: 

    - security foundation
        a) establish the governance, risk management, and compliance standards that define your orgs security policies. 
            e.g., which AWS regions are permitted, which regulary standards (HIPAA, etc.) must be met, etc. 

        b) separate workloads into distinct AWS accounts (for production, development, security, etc.).
            Centrally manage these accounts using AWS Organizations.
            This ensures a breach of one AWS account doesn't effect the whole business.

        c) apply Service Control Policies (SCPs) to your AWS accounts. 
            This sets the "maximum allowed permissions" for every user and service in an account. 
            It prevents even an Admin from performing high-risk actions (like deleting audit trails, disabling logging).

        The security foundation should be in place before any developer launches a resource.

    - identity and access management 
        strictly control who can access resources.
        users and services should only have the permissions that are required to complete their tasks. 

    - detection
        use automated tools and monitoring to immediately identify unauthorized activity or configuration changes. 

    - infrastructure protection 
        secure the network (VPCs) and compute resources (instances) that host your workloads. 
        your should secure them from both external and internal threats.

    - data protection 
        use encryption, versioning, and access policies. 
        your goal is to maintain both confidentiality and data integrity.

    - incident response  
        you should develop a process for responding to security events, and regularly simulate the events. 
        the goal is to minimize damage and ensure rapid recovery.

    - application security 
        to acheive this, security scanning and testing should be integrated into the CI/CD process

It's important to understand the Shared Responsibility Model. 
    It distinguishes what Amazon will secure (the cloud itself) vs. what you must secure (what's in the cloud). 

    What Amazon secures depends on what type of services it is (IaaS, PaaS, SaaS): 
    - IaaS (e.g. EC2)
        AWS secures the physical data centers, hardware, cooling, and virtualization layer 
        Customer secures the guest OS (updates and patching), network configs (VPCs and Security Groups), data encryption, user identities
    
    - PaaS (e.g. Lambda, RDS)
        AWS secures the physical infrastructure plus the underlying OS, database engine patching, runtime environment.
        Customer secures the application code, data classification, and access to the service. 

    - SaaS (e.g. Chiem, QuickSight) 
        AWS secures the entire tech stack, including infrastructure, OS, data, and the application code 
        Customer secures only the user auth (who can log in) and access to the data passed to the service


Security design principles: 

    - Implement a strong identification system. 
        Ensure users and services only have permissions they need for their task (least privilege principle).
        Centralize identity management. 
        Migrate off of long term, static credentials that can be easily compromised. 

    - Monitor and log actions / changes in the environment.
        Integrate the logs with automated systems that immediately investgiate suspicious activity / trigger alerts. 

    - Apply security at all layers.
        This includes the network edge, VPC, load balancers, compute instances, and application code. 

    - Define and manage security controls as code. Put it in templates under version control.
        This allows you to scale security, and reduces the risk of configuration errors. 

    - Protect data in transit and at rest. 
        Classify data based on sensitivity, then apply appropriate protections (encryption, tokenization).
        Ensure data is guarded while in transit and at rest (doesn't Amazon do this for us?). 

    - Keep people away from data. 
        Minimize the need for humans to directly access or manually process the data. 
        Use automated tools for data handling (prevents accidental corruption). 

    - Prepare for security events.
        Establish incident response processes and formal policies. 
        Regularly run security simulations to test whether you can detect, investigate, and recover from incidents. 


A threat model is a representation of all the ways someone could attack your system.
    Construct a threat model based on industry best practices, and keep it updated. 

Automate security tasks to ensure they scale and are performed reliably. 

It's important to separate workloads (based on function or data sensitivity) across separate AWS accounts. 
    It limits the blast radius of an attack. 

Good Identity and Access Management (IAM) ensures only authenticated users / machines can interact with resources. 
    Centralize the identities of users / machines and enforce proper auth (multi-factor / password policies).

The principle of least privilege is important (only granting permissions necessary for a task). 
    To maintain this, the use of temporary credentials is best practice (issued through AWS Security Token Service). 
    For developers, AWS's IAM Identity Center can provide controlled access to CLIs or SDKs.
        This will provide short-lived tokens instead of long-term static access keys.


Preventative controls (e.g. IAM, Firewalls) block bad code, unauthorized access, malicious actions, etc..
Detective controls are the logs and alerts which alert the security team to events. 
    To have good detective controls you first need good operational baselines, 
    so that you can know when behavior becomes anomalous. 


Amazon CloudTrail records events. Every time something calls an AWS API it gets recorded by CloudTrail.
Amazon Config contains the current state of all the distributed resources.
    It also tracks how those configs have changed over the last 6 months. 
Threat Intelligence is a collection of known malicious threat signatures. 
    AWS & their partners (CrowdStrike, ProofPoint) have identified these signatures across the internet:
        - malicious IPs 
        - Tor Exit Nodes (anonymous proxies often used to hide attacks)
        - Crypto mining pools (known addresses where hijacked servers send mined crypto)
        - C2 Domains (Command and Control - domains used by malware to receive malicious instructions from the hacker)

Amazon GuardDuty is the threat detection layer.
    It uses ML to cross reference the logs from CloudTrail / Config with Threat Intelligence to find patterns. 
    Examples of patterns include: 
        - a developers credentials being used from a known malicious IP in a country you don't operate in 
        - an EC2 instance that starts communicating with a Bitcoin mining pool or a C2 server
        - unusual patterns of data being pulled from a sensitive bucket

    Examining the CloudTrail logs yourself would be impossible since they're too large and full of noise. 
    GuardDuty monitors continuously.

Amazon EventBridge is a central orchestrator for events. 
    It can be used to bridge the gap between detection (GuardDuty) and programmatic response.
    GuardDuty's findings can be ingested by EventBridge. 
    When a finding matches a predefined rule, EventBridge can broadcast an event. 
        This can trigger alerts (Amazon SNS) or automated remediation logic (AWS Lambda) downstream. 

    You can also pipe these events to CloudWatch to trigger alerts in response to aggregated statistics.
    Amazon CloudWatch provides statistical monitoring. 
        It aggregates statistics into metrics, hosts centralized logs for audit purposes, 
        and it can trigger alarms if metrics exceed thresholds.

Forensics is the process of reconstructing a security incident after it has occurred.
    You need this for legal reasons and for fixing the vulnerabilities.
Governments and industries also establish regulations you must adhere to (HIPAA, PCI, SOC2, etc.)
    Most regulations require you keep logs for a period of time. 
        If during an audit you do not have the logs, you can face fines / lose certification.

Structured Log Management ensures your data is kept consistent and searchable to meet forensic and regularoy needs.

    Short term data is often stored in CloudWatch, where it's live, indexed, and visible in dashboards / monitoring. 
    For long term storage it's often moved to S3 (specifically Glacier tiers). 

    AWS can automate the entire logging lifecycle - collection, storage, archiving, and deletion.
        
        Cloudwatch Retention Policies determine how long data remains in Cloudwatch before it's purged.
            To move the logs into S3 before they're purged you'd use Kinesis Data Firehose or a CloudWatch Export Task.
                Kinesis Data Firehose would be used for real time streaming (e.g. near-instant cold storage analysis).
                Cloudwatch Export Task is batched, and data may take up to ~12 hours to become available. 
        
        S3 Lifecycle Policies can automatically transition aging data through cost-optimized storage tiers
            (e.g., S3 Standard → Glacier Deep Archive) based on the age of the record.
            S3 Object Lock's WORM protections (write once, read many) also satisfy legal requirements.
    
        Automated logging ensures the data is handled reliably and cost effectively.


To guard infrastructure you typically setup multiple layers of security throughout the network and compute resources,
    and guard against both internal and external threats. 
    This is known as a "defense of depth" strategy.

    At the network level, this is achieved using Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC).
        VPC allows you to setup subnets, routing tables, and packet inspection for a highly controlled network topology.
        Security is achieved by enforcing strict boundary protection and monitoring all points of ingress and egress. 

    For compute resources, protection involves: 
    - comprehensive logging and continuous monitoring to identify anomalies
    - hardening, a practice where secure configurations are persisted in immutable Amazon Machine Images (AMIs).
        hardening ensures that any new instance, even automated ones, has the same secure configurations.  


Data must be properly classified by sensitivity. 
    This allows you to determine the right security and retention policy for it. 

Critical data must be encrypted to support both financial security and regularity compliance. 
In AWS, the user maintains full ownership of their data, and decides which region it's stored in. 
    Data stays within its designated region unless explicitly moved by the user. 

To protect data at rest AWS uses KMS and SSE. 

AWS Key Management Service (KMS) provides automated key management as a centralized service.
    This handles the entire key lifecycle: generation, storage, distribution, rotation, and retirement. 
    Automating this reduces human error and ensures security standards (like regular rotation) are met consistently.

AWS provides Server-Side Encryption (SSE), which encrypts data before writing it to disk and decrypts during retrieval. 
    In Amazon S3, SSE is implemented in 3 different models. 
    The models differ in who manages the encryption keys and the level of control / auditability they provide:

        SSE-S3      the most integrated and automated option. AWS manages the data keys entirely.
                        this is the default model used by all new S3 buckets. 
                        the only downside is it offers limited visibility in the lifecycle of the keys. 

        SSE-KMS     builds on the automation of SSE-S3 but integrates AWS KMS, providing more control / auditability. 
                        The KMS key policy also acts as a second layer of protection. 
                        You can use either an AWS-managed KMS key or a customer-managed KMS key. 
                        AWS CloudTrail also logs an event every time a key is used to encrypt or decrypt something.
                            Often times an audit trail like this is required for regulatory compliance (HIPAA, SOC2)
                        At scale, SSE-KMS also allows you to use S3 Bucket Keys. These are temporary, bucket-level keys 
                            which you can use to decrypt data without pinging KMS too frequently. 
                            Otherwise, you'd need to query KMS every time you upload or download an object,
                                which could mean high costs / hitting KMS throttling limits during high traffic. 
        
        SSE-C       This is for customer provided keys. It's useful in special cases where the customer must 
                        physically possess and manage the keys themselves. The customer provides the encryption key 
                        with every HTTP request when uploading or downloading an object. S3 uses the provided key
                        to perform the encryption or decryption, then immediately discards it. 
                        This places the responsibility managing the keys lifecycle on the customer.  
                        If a key is lost, the data becomes unrecoverable, since AWS has no record of it. 
                        As of April 2026, AWS has disabled SSE-C by default for new buckets, prioritizing the more
                            auditable SSE-KMS. SSE-C isn't being phased out but must be explicitly enabled. 

AWS S3 provides extreme durability (99.999999999% - 11 9's), which guarantees the encrypted data persists. 
You can also enable versioning on an S3 bucket, which will guard against accidental overwrites of the data. 
    By default, the versioning will track state indefinitely (though that can be reconfigured, since it's expensive).
And you can enable S3 data events, which will record in CloudTrail every API call made to the S3 bucket. 
    It'll identify the user / role responsible for the action, and what action they performed. 
    The SSE-KMS logging tells you which keys were used, but the S3 logging tells you which files were accessed.
        

To protect data in transit AWS uses TLS. 

SSL termitation (aka SSL offloading) is when an SSL connection is terminated at proxy (usually a load balancer),
    decrypted, then forwarded to internal servers. 

    It reduces the CPU burden placed on the internal servers, 
        because the proxy can be optimized for the decryption.  
    
    It also greatly simplifies certificate management - instead of installing and renewing certificates 
        on every internal server, only the proxy's must be renewed. 
        In AWS certificates are managed via AWS Certificate Manager (ACM), which automates their renewal / deployment.

In SSL bridging the load balancer terminates the initial connection to inspect the traffic for security threats 
    then immediately re-encrypts the data.
In End-to-End encryption the data is kept encrypted.

SSL termination does make internal traffic unencrypted, but that's often considered an acceptable tradeoff 
    because it occurs within a VPC (Virtual Private Cloud). 
However, organizations with high security requirements or strict regularly compliance requirements
    may require SSL Bridging or End-to-End Encryption instead. 


Behind the scenes, AWS uses Software Defined Networking (SDN) to manage network configurations.
    This is a system which separates the logical network configuration from physical network devices. 
    It consists of three layers: 

        SDN Control Plane
            This is the API users / applications interact with to make network changes. It's a regional service.
            It validates the changes against account limits and IAM permissions, then translates them into instructions.
            The instructions are sent to distributed network components, which store them in their local caches.

        SDN Mapping Service
            Since the VPC is an overlay network (a virtual, logical network built on top of the physical network),
            the private IP addresses within the VPC don't correspond with IPs of physical servers. 
            The Mapping Service is what maps the VPCs virtual IPs to physical servers.
                It contains a massive, real-time record of every virtual entity (MAC and IP addresses) 
                and the physical servers they're associated with. 
                To send a message over the VPC network AWS queries this service to determine the physical route to take.

        SDN Data Plane (Nitro and Hyperplane)

            Every AWS server has an AWS Nitro Card installed on it. This is a specialized network card that 
            processes AWS's network packets very efficiently. It wraps / unwraps packets, enforces 
            Security Groups rules (at the hardware level), and handles hardware-level encryption. 

            In traditional networking, firewalls / load balancers / NAT gateways maintain state for active connections.
                The state consists of the source / destination IP and ports. 
                It's necessary for routing return traffic, maintaining security context (for analysis of permitted connections), and for handshake-based internet protocols (like TCP).

            In a cloud context, the memory limits of these physical network devices don't scale enough.
                After a traditional devices memory limit is hit (which often happens during network spikes), 
                    it'll need to connect with secondary storage to continue operating.
                    That's slow and introduces distributed state management complexity.

            AWS Hyperplane is a high performance, distributed network state management system.
                When a packet enters the VPC, Hyperplane uses hashing to assign the packet to a subset of its nodes. 
                The state information is replicated across multiple nodes, ensuring connections are maintained reliably. 

                Hyperplane also handles volatile traffic spikes by scaling up nodes while shifting data / resharding.

    AWS's VPC Router is not a physical or virtual machine, it's an SDN function implemented using Nitro Cards 
        and the Mapping Service. It's thousands of Nitro Cards working together to enforce network configs / 
        routing tables / security policies. 

        The Nitro Card consults its local hardware cache (regularly updated via the Control Plane) to determine
            the packets destination. 
            
            If the packet is destined for another instance within the same VPC, the Nitro Card queries the Mapping  
                Service to resolve the address. It wraps the packet and sends it off. Upon arrival, the destination's
                Nitro Card unwraps it.
        
            If the packet is destined to a regional edge device (e.g. Internet Gateway or Virtual Private Gateway), 
                the Nitro Card ensures the packet is translated properly before forwarding it. 

        The VPC router's distributed design scales infinitely since every new server contains a Nitro Card.
            In contrast, traditional routers have a limited backplane or memory.

        The VPC router is also where VPC encryption is applied and enforced. 
            When the packet passes through the Nitro Card, AWS enforces hardware-level encryption independent of
            the OS. AWS's VPC Encryption Controls provide "transparent" encryption for all traffic.
            Note that this link-layer encryption guards data on the wire, but is gone by the time it reaches the OS. 



        
        The primary function of the routing tables is to define the "Public" or "Private" status of a subnet. Although an Internet Gateway is attached to the VPC as a whole, it remains dormant for any specific subnet until that subnet’s route table is updated with a "Default Route" ($0.0.0.0/0$) pointing to the gateway. This architectural choice places the power of network segmentation directly in the hands of the architect. By creating a custom route table and associating it with a specific subnet, you effectively create a logical boundary. You can ensure that your database tier, for example, has no route to the internet at all, while your web tier uses its route table to communicate with the outside world.In modern 2026 architectures, this routing layer is also where the VPC Encryption Controls and Gateway Load Balancers are integrated. By manipulating the routes, you can force traffic to move through a specific sequence of "inspection" subnets before it ever reaches its final destination. This "Next Hop" logic allows you to treat the route table as a programmable switchboard, directing traffic through firewalls, intrusion detection systems, or private service endpoints, all while the underlying hardware ensures that every byte remains encrypted and isolated from other tenants in the AWS ecosystem.


In AWS, the Internet Gateway connects the public internet to the VPC. 


        Technically, this statement is partially accurate but incomplete, and that missing nuance is exactly what leads to security vulnerabilities in network design.At the infrastructure level, an Internet Gateway (IGW) is a horizontally scaled, redundant, and highly available software-defined component. While we often describe it as "connecting" the internet to the VPC, it is more accurate to describe it as a translator and a doorway. It provides a target in your VPC route tables for internet-bound traffic and performs Static Network Address Translation (Static NAT) for instances that have been assigned public IP addresses.The "accuracy" problem in your statement lies in the word "connects," which implies an automatic, open pipe. In reality, attaching an IGW to a VPC does absolutely nothing to your traffic until two other conditions are met at the subnet and instance levels.First, the infrastructure-level software (the VPC Router) must be programmed via a Route Table to recognize the IGW. Even if an IGW is attached to the VPC, a subnet remains "private" and isolated from the internet until a route is explicitly added that directs traffic destined for the outside world ($0.0.0.0/0$) to that specific Gateway. Without this instruction, the "connection" between the internet and that specific segment of your network does not exist.Second, the IGW only facilitates communication for instances that possess a Public IP address. Because VPCs use private address ranges (such as $10.0.0.0/16$), the public internet has no way of routing packets back to those internal addresses. The Internet Gateway manages this by maintaining a 1-to-1 mapping between an instance's private IP and its public IP. When traffic leaves the VPC, the IGW swaps the private source address for the public one; when traffic returns, it performs the reverse.Therefore, a more precise architectural definition would be: The Internet Gateway is a VPC-level edge component that enables communication between the VPC and the internet by serving as a routing target and performing address translation, but it only facilitates "connectivity" for subnets and instances that are explicitly configured to use it.



VPC subnets are isolated parts of a VPCs IP address range (configured by dividing up CIDR blocks). 
    Subnets ared used to hierarchically structure a private network (e.g., setting a tiered architecture).
        This is beneficial for security - you establish entry points to the subnet and control access in and out.

    


    In AWS, a subnet's first 4 IPs and last IP are reserved (DNS, VPC router, network address, etc.). 
    
    A VPC spans an entire AWS Region, but a VPC subnet is isolated to one Availability Zone. 



AWS's Elastic Load Balancer (ELB) is a distributed service consisting of a service plane and data plane.
    The data plane consists of worker nodes, which are load balancers of various types.
    Each VPC subnet (which is tied to a single availability zone) will have at least 1 load balancer node. 
    


        The Service Plane (The Orchestrator)
        The Service Plane (often called the Control Plane) is the administrative "brain" of the system. It handles the logic, configuration, and monitoring of the load balancer without ever touching the actual data packets. Its primary responsibilities include:

        Configuration Management: Processing API calls to create or update listeners, target groups, and security settings.

        Orchestration: Monitoring the health of backend targets and communicating those status changes to the data plane.

        Elasticity: Watching traffic metrics and automatically provisioning or removing worker nodes in the data plane to handle fluctuations in demand.

        The Data Plane (The Muscle)
        The Data Plane consists of the actual Worker Nodes—managed resources deployed into your specific VPC subnets. This is where the "heavy lifting" occurs:

        Traffic Processing: These nodes intercept incoming requests, perform SSL/TLS decryption (for ALB/NLB), and execute routing logic to forward traffic to the healthiest backend target.

        Physical Presence: Unlike the regional service plane, the data plane is zonal. If you enable three Availability Zones, AWS places worker nodes in all three to ensure high availability.

        Implementation Variance: The nature of these nodes changes by type: ALB nodes are software-based reverse proxies, while NLB nodes are hardware-accelerated interfaces powered by the AWS Hyperplane for massive throughput.




        To understand ELB (Elastic Load Balancing) fundamentally, you have to distinguish between the Service Plane (the brand and management tools) and the Data Plane (the actual "workers" that move your traffic).1. ELB as a "Management Plane"Specifically, ELB is an AWS Managed Service Framework. It is not a single piece of hardware; it is a set of APIs and control logic that manages specialized resources on your behalf.When you "create an ELB," you are actually instructing AWS to provision a fleet of managed resources (Load Balancer Nodes) into your VPC. ELB acts as the "brain" that:Auto-Scales: It monitors the traffic hitting your load balancer and automatically adds or removes the underlying "balancer nodes" to handle the load.Health Monitoring: It constantly "pings" your backend targets (EC2, Lambda, etc.) and updates its internal routing table to avoid dead servers.DNS Integration: It provides a stable DNS name (like my-load-balancer-1234.us-east-1.elb.amazonaws.com) and manages the underlying IP addresses so you don't have to.2. The Relationship Between ELB and the Specific BalancersYou can think of ELB as the "Parent Class" in a software project, while the ALB, NLB, and GLB are the "Child Classes" that inherit basic properties but perform very different specific jobs.ComponentWhat it is exactlyELB ServiceThe AWS "wrapper" that handles billing, API calls, CloudWatch metrics, and high-level scaling logic.ALB (The Specialist)A Layer 7 Application Proxy. It's a fleet of managed software instances that can "read" your HTTP traffic.NLB (The Speedster)A Layer 4 Flow-Hash Engine. It uses specialized AWS hardware (Hyperplane) to route packets without looking inside them.GWLB (The Bridge)A Layer 3 Gateway. It creates a transparent tunnel to send all your traffic through a security appliance (like a firewall) and back.3. The "Invisible" InfrastructureOne of the most common misconceptions is that an ELB is a single virtual machine. In reality, an ELB consists of:Nodes i